                    "file": "service_files/obmc-power-start@.service",
                    "line": 16,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Ian Woloschin",
                        "email": "ian.woloschin@akamai.com",
                        "username": "iwoloschin"
                    },
                    "message": "Pardon me for asking what is probably a bad question, but is the intention here that this service is called for system power on and the platform will need to provide a suitable daemon (phosphor-power? Something else platform specific if phosphor-power is not suitable?) and that daemon would handle any actual power on/off actions?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "service_files/obmc-power-start@.service",
                    "line": 16,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrew Geissler",
                        "email": "andrew@geissonator.com",
                        "username": "geissonator"
                    },
                    "message": "Yeah, the (unwritten?) rule is that if you want to use phosphor-state-manager, something must implement the org.openbmc.control.Power interface if you wish to power on/off your chassis. Currently within OpenBMC that's either from the phosphor-power repo or the op-pwrctl piece of phosphor-skeleton.\n\nNext up after these changes is to take some of the community feedback and improve on PSM documentation."
                },
                {
                    "file": "service_files/obmc-power-start@.service",
                    "line": 16,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Ian Woloschin",
                        "email": "ian.woloschin@akamai.com",
                        "username": "iwoloschin"
                    },
                    "message": "Ok great, thank you for confirming!"
                }
            ],
